Posted: Tue Jun 26, 2012 8:08 pm
Frennzy wrote:Quote:Where a bunch of firefighters in the early 90's....what? Found love on a two-way street?Died. Upslope winds caught them offguard.I used to do some work with wildland fire crews. That incident? It's even scarier than that. What they figure happened is that some of the combustible volatiles being driven out of every damn thing anywhere near the fire collected on the slope, and then flashed over. There was a distinct lack of shake n bake bags* on the corpses.*Shelter bags for jumpers, intended for when you're pretty much fucked. Theory is, you get in the bag and let the fire run over you. Sometimes they actually work.Funny looking at those pics. I remember taking pics of a fire that was in the process of fucking off (a highly technical term, indicating a combination of class 5-6 fire behavior, some wind, and fire's complete disregard for the designs of man) and figuring they'd look amazing. Sounded like a couple hundred jet engines, could see huge chunks of flaming tree flying half a kilometer through the air, yadda yadda.Didn't look like much when I got home and developed them. Frennzy's look worse. Fast guess, one of those pics has flames 200 meters high in it, if not more. That's some SERIOUS shit there. The good news is that the tree density in those pics looks lower than what I'm used to, so the fire won't move quite so easily. Then again, "less" is still too much.Frennzy, you got a lot of black pine there?
grendelmk1
